Modulating Composition – Effect of Ni/Fe ratio: As depicted in Fig. 5A, NiFe LDH with 1:1 Ni/Fe ratio shows better performance towards OER than the rest of the compositions. The Ni2+/Ni3+ oxidation peak arises around 1.3 V overlaps with the onset potential [72]. Fig. S9 shows the portions of LSV curves enlarged in the 1.2–1.4 V potential region, evidently depicting that the measurement of actual onset potential becomes somewhat difficult due to this minor oxidation peak. So, all the overpotentials are reported at a higher current density of 100 mAcm−2 avoiding the Ni redox region. Fig. 5B compares LSVs measured for NFL, NFL/CNT, CQD/NFL, and CQD/NFL/CNT along with that of the RuO2 electrocatalyst. The overpotentials and Tafel slopes calculated from the LSV graphs that depict the OER kinetics of the electrodes are shown in Fig. 5C as a bar chart. At 100 mAcm−2 current density, the NiFe LDH with 1:1 Ni/Fe ratio shows the lowest overpotential of 201 mV when compared to the other electrodes prepared by varying the Ni/Fe ratios- 2:1 (263 mV), 3:1 (228 mV), 1:2 (216 mV), and 1:3 (256 mV). Also reported in the same figure are the LSV curves of CNT-coated nickel foam- CNT/NF (249 mV), RuO2 coated nickel foam- RuO2/NF (278 mV), and bare nickel foam-bare NF (297 mV) (Fig. 5A). The highest overpotential for bare nickel foam than the catalyst-coated Ni foams indicates that as-synthesized NiFe LDHs with varying Ni/Fe ratios are better OER catalysts and effectively reduce the needed overpotentials to facilitate OER in alkaline conditions. Also, all ratios of NiFe LDHs show better performance towards OER than the conventional RuO2 electrocatalysts. It is remarkable that the observed overpotentials (201–256 mV) at 100 mAcm−2 current density are lower or comparable to most reports in the literature at 10 mAcm−2, a much lower current density [40,73]. As observed from Fig. 5A, Fig. S10 and the literature (Table 1
), there are no clear trends in overpotentials for OER with increasing Ni/Fe ratio in NiFe LDHs [74,75]. On the other hand, the overpotentials for OER increase while the Ni/Fe ratio in NiFe LDH decreases. These are similar to other reports in the literature [76]. In this scenario, confining Ni/Fe ratio to one (1:1) provides optimal synergy between Ni and Fe active sites and the NiOOH and FeOOH intermediate species in the reaction mechanism, providing improved OER rates [25] (Scheme 2
). The calculated Tafel slopes are 61.8, 71.1, 46.1, 50, 47.5, 50.3, 47.5, and 66.9 mVdec−1 for NiFe LDHs with Ni/Fe ratios 3:1, 2:1, 1:1, 1:2, 1:3, RuO2/NF, CNT/NF, and bare NF respectively (Fig. S10). The Tafel slopes also do not follow a trend with varying Ni/Fe ratios in NiFe LDH. However, the NiFe LDH with Ni/Fe ratio 1:1 shows the lowest Tafel slope of 46.1 mVdec−1, denoting superior reaction kinetics among all the compositions.
